// AUTO-GENERATED for gi_final from the GI 31-34 + 35-38 delta docs (assemble_gi_final.py). Regenerate, don't hand-edit.

const QUIZ_CONFIG = {"id": "gi_final", "title": "GI Final", "emoji": "🩺"};
const IMAGES = {};
const LO_ANSWERS = {"31_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Dr. Blavo opens by deliberately downscoping the microbiology — \"we've given enough talks on those organisms\" — so the move he wants from you is not a memorized list but a pattern. Every organism collapses into one of three stool behaviors: inflammatory (EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter), secretory (ETEC, Vibrio cholerae), and osmotic (rotavirus, norovirus, EPEC, Giardia). Once you know the pattern, the workup and the fluids follow — so learn the buckets, not the encyclopedia.", "why": "E. coli O157:H7 — it causes HUS, and unlike the rest it is made worse by antibiotics, so the stakes of recognizing it are highest."}, "31_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. For diarrhea, the history is the diagnostic test — Blavo's whole \"rote-to-rationale\" message is that you ask each question for a reason. The single most useful question is the character of the stool: loose, watery, mucoid, bloody, oily, or foul-smelling. Each adjective points somewhere.", "why": "Blood/leukocytes (inflammatory), stool volume (voluminous = secretory), and fat/odor or response to fasting (osmotic/malabsorptive) sort almost every case."}, "31_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. There is no rigid formal classification, but the working schema gastroenterologists carry — and the one that organizes your whole differential — is inflammatory vs non-inflammatory, with non-inflammatory splitting into secretory and osmotic. The classification is the differential diagnosis.", "why": "Secretory — an enterotoxin is actively driving secretion, so the lumen stays wet even without ingested solute; an osmotic diarrhea would have slowed or stopped with fasting."}, "31_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Most diarrhea is mild, self-limited, and needs no workup at all — observation, fluids, and anticipatory guidance. You investigate only when a red flag raises the stakes: moderate/severe dehydration, an ill child or elderly patient, bloody or voluminous stool, duration >48 h, high fever, severe abdominal pain, recent antibiotics, or an immunocompromised host.", "why": "You choose the single study that confirms a named hypothesis (the red-flag pattern points to it), rather than ordering a broad panel and hoping something turns up."}, "31_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Management is mostly rehydration, because most infectious diarrhea is self-limited — the body heals itself if you keep it in a workable fluid and electrolyte state. Blavo's childhood memory of a cholera outbreak in Ghana, and his later cholera intervention in Haiti, anchor the stakes: secretory losses can kill through dehydration even when the patient doesn't look classically \"septic.\" Oral rehydration is first-line.", "why": "Glucose drives sodium-coupled absorption (SGLT1) so water is reabsorbed even while the gut secretes; Coca-Cola's glucose-to-sodium ratio is backwards and hyperosmolar, so it pulls water into the lumen instead."}, "33_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Endoscopy for a GI bleed turns on two questions: is the patient hemodynamically stable or unstable, and where is the source. Unstable patients (hypotensive, tachycardic, syncope) get volume and, if exsanguinating, unmatched blood — you resuscitate before you scope.", "why": "A fast upper bleed (e.g., duodenal ulcer) presents as maroon stool from below, and unlike most lower sources you can actually stop it endoscopically — so the top is scoped first."}, "33_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Beyond the standard EGD and colonoscopy, three scopes are each defined by what they can do. The trick is to tag each one diagnostic, therapeutic, or both.", "why": "EUS — it stages and biopsies the mass through the gastric wall, assesses vascular involvement and nodes in one step; percutaneous biopsy risks tract seeding and undersampling."}, "33_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Upper endoscopy (EGD) sees from the oropharynx to the second portion of the duodenum. The biggest indication is GERD — and the reason to scope reflux is to look for Barrett's esophagus, a silent change in the lining.", "why": "Whether liquids get stuck too: solids-only points to a structural narrowing; solids-and-liquids points to a motility disorder (work it up with barium first)."}, "33_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Colonoscopy diagnoses the colorectal differential and removes polyps, but for bleeding its therapeutic reach is limited. The high-yield separations are the diverticular pair and the IBD patterns.", "why": "Diverticulosis — acute, painless, significant hematochezia over 50 that self-limits ~80% of the time; endoscopic therapy for lower bleeds is limited, so management is largely supportive after excluding an upper source."}, "33_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Indications run through the other LOs; the complications and contraindications are the testable headlines. ERCP is the most dangerous procedure gastroenterologists perform, with an overall complication rate around 10%. Its signature complication is post-ERCP pancreatitis — you are working at the tiny opening where the bile and pancreatic ducts meet, so even a flawless operator can inflame the pancreas.", "why": "ERCP — about a 10% complication rate, and its signature complication is post-ERCP pancreatitis from manipulating the shared bile/pancreatic-duct opening."}, "33_6": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Schneider calls screening his primary responsibility — and the single highest-yield block. The logic is the adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence: precancerous adenomatous polyps become cancer over roughly a decade, so we scope to find and remove them.", "why": "Colonoscopy is offered FIRST and is the only test that also prevents cancer by removing polyps; a stool test (annual FIT) is for patients who decline colonoscopy — it detects cancer but doesn't prevent it, and Cologuard is not equivalent."}, "35_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar anchors the entire lecture on one picture: the parietal cell and the H⁺/K⁺-ATPase proton pump that does the actual work of secreting hydrogen ions into the gastric lumen in exchange for K⁺. Everything you study after this — every drug class — is just a different way of getting at that pump, so it pays to fix the wiring now. Four signals converge on it: three stimulate, one restrains.", "why": "ON: acetylcholine (M3), histamine (H2), and gastrin (CCK-B) all activate kinases that drive the H+/K+-ATPase. DOWN: PGE2 (EP receptors) inhibits secretion and is cytoprotective."}, "35_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This is the workhorse LO — Parmar marches one class per slide on a fixed template (mechanism / uses / adverse effects), and he is explicit that you should learn the class logic rather than memorize every interchangeable agent. The organizing spine is a potency ladder: antacids neutralize, H2RAs block a receptor, PPIs and PCABs hit the pump itself. Climb the ladder and acid suppression deepens.", "why": "Antacid (transient neutralization) < H2RA (~60-70%, tachyphylaxis) < PPI (>90%, irreversible) < PCAB (reversible K-competition). Signature AEs: Al/Mg bowel shift, cimetidine antiandrogen/CYP, PPI B12-Mg-fracture-C.diff, misoprostol pregnancy CI."}, "35_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The whole point of this LO is one comparison: H2RA versus PPI. Parmar drew the contrast explicitly in numbers, and the exam loves it because the two drugs sit on the same pathway but act at different points — a receptor versus the pump.", "why": "The PPI wins on potency (>90% vs ~60-70%) and durability (irreversible pump block, no tachyphylaxis). The long-term cost is decreased B12 bioavailability, because the acid that normally frees B12 from dietary protein is suppressed."}, "35_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar flagged the interaction material directly — “focus from exam point of view, this is important” — while warning that the full list reads as an unmemorizable laundry. The way through is to sort by mechanism: enzyme inhibition (CYP), a change in gastric pH, and physical binding/chelation. Get the three buckets and any specific pair is predictable.", "why": "CYP inhibition: cimetidine (warfarin/diazepam/eletriptan) and omeprazole/esomeprazole + clopidogrel (CYP2C19). Raised gastric pH: PPIs impairing digoxin/azole absorption. Binding: sucralfate + quinolones, and antacids chelating tetracyclines/iron — space dosing 2-4 h."}, "35_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar time-boxed this to a few minutes but framed it as high-stakes — H. pylori is a common infection linked to peptic ulcer disease and an established risk factor for gastric adenocarcinoma and MALT lymphoma. The cancer link is the reason eradication is taken seriously, and the reason the rules tightened in the 2024 guidelines.", "why": "14-day Optimized BQT (PPI + tetracycline + metronidazole + bismuth) is gold standard; clarithromycin was dropped for resistance, with PCAB-dual and rifabutin-triple as alternatives. After 14 days, confirmation of eradication (fecal antigen, urea breath test, or biopsy) is mandatory."}, "35_6": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar builds this whole lecture as a receptor map, so the first move is to learn the categories, not the individual drugs. Nausea and vomiting are integrated at the chemoreceptor trigger zone (CTZ) / area postrema and the vomiting center, and four neurotransmitter-receptor pairs feed them: ACh (M1), histamine (H1), substance P (NK1), and serotonin (5-HT3). Each pair has a drug class that blocks it. Two adjunct families — cannabinoids (CB1 agonists) and benzodiazepines (GABA-A modulators) — plus dexamethasone and olanzapine round out the rescue/adjuvant tier.", "why": "ACh/M1 (scopolamine), histamine/H1 (meclizine, dimenhydrinate), substance P/NK1 (the -pitants), and serotonin/5-HT3 (the -setrons) — the four receptors that organize the entire antiemetic toolkit."}, "35_7": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The mechanism story is the heart of the lecture, and Parmar tells it as one vomiting-reflex framework: stimuli converge on the CTZ/area postrema and the vomiting center in the floor of the fourth ventricle, and each antiemetic class simply blocks one input. Get the framework first and every drug's MOA is just \"which receptor does it sit on.\"", "why": "The immediate episode is serotonin acting at 5-HT3 (acute phase) — covered by a setron; the day-3 episode is substance P acting at NK1 (delayed phase) — covered by a -pitant. Highly emetogenic regimens combine both plus dexamethasone."}, "35_8": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Therapeutic uses cluster around a short vocabulary you'll see repeated on every slide — CINV (chemotherapy-induced), PONV (postoperative), RINV (radiation-induced), motion sickness, and gastroparesis. Because the indications overlap so heavily, the exam discriminates by adverse effect: each class has a signature toxicity, and that's where Parmar spends his emphasis.", "why": "Both block D2 and cause EPS, but metoclopramide's boxed warning is irreversible tardive dyskinesia (cap therapy at 12 weeks), while droperidol's is QT prolongation/torsades (mandatory 12-lead ECG before and 2-3 hours after dosing)."}, "35_9": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Two interaction themes carry this LO, and Parmar flags both as testable: the Parkinson's contraindication that follows every dopamine blocker, and the CYP-P450 interactions of the NK1 antagonists — which he ties directly to COMLEX drug-interaction questions after talking to a student who took the exam.", "why": "Aprepitant inhibits CYP3A4, the enzyme that clears dexamethasone, so dexamethasone accumulates and its dose must be reduced; rolapitant inhibits CYP2D6 instead, leaving CYP3A4-mediated dexamethasone metabolism untouched, so no adjustment is needed."}, "37_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Rose opens the way an old-school trauma surgeon does: before he lays a hand on the patient he pictures what's going on inside — skin, fascia, muscle, and peritoneum stripped away, the organs laid bare. The whole lecture rests on this. For trauma the single most useful map is the four quadrants, because the quadrant plus the mechanism tells you which organs are at risk. (The finer nine-region map — epigastric, umbilical, hypogastric, and the paired hypochondriac, lumbar, and iliac regions — is for localizing abdominal pain, not trauma.)", "why": "Picturing the organs by quadrant lets the mechanism predict the injury: knowing what is fixed vs mobile, and what sits in the struck quadrant, tells you which organs to look for before any imaging."}, "37_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. If Rose makes one point in this lecture, it is ultrasound: that's the thing that's going to make all the difference. The bedside FAST exam (Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma) is fast, cheap, repeatable, and increasingly done on a phone probe — he told the class to chase the ultrasound teams in the ED and learn it. FAST hunts for free fluid (blood), air, and gross organ injury in the liver, kidneys, and spleen, and the density of the fluid even distinguishes blood from serous fluid. The volume of blood in the abdomen can be estimated from it.", "why": "Because stability — not the FAST result — drives disposition: the unstable patient is exsanguinating and goes straight to the OR, while the one who responds to crystalloid has bought the time for a CT and a trial of observation."}, "37_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The mechanism tells you what to look for, so name it. Blunt / compression (the common one) drives organs against the spine and breaks ribs over the spleen and liver. Penetrating (stab, gunshot) injures along its trajectory — and the trajectory, not just the entry point, is what matters: a wound below the nipple line can cross the diaphragm into the abdomen because the diaphragm rides up to the nipples on expiration. Crush is severe compression (steering wheel, a wall). Iatrogenic injury is caused by us during an operation. Blast injury drives foreign bodies inward and combines penetrating with crush.", "why": "The path determines which organs the object actually crossed; a wound's entry point can be misleading, since a sub-nipple or angled trajectory may cross the diaphragm or track retroperitoneally and spare or strike organs far from the entry site."}, "37_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This is the heart of the lecture, and the spleen is its center. The spleen is the most frequently injured organ in blunt abdominal trauma and the most common reason for splenectomy in the U.S. Its capsule is paper-thin and its attachments (gastrosplenic ligament, attachments to the diaphragm) tear easily. Injury comes from penetrating, blunt, or iatrogenic mechanisms — and isolated splenic injury occurs in only about 30% of cases, so when you find a hurt spleen, look for the stomach, left kidney, pancreas, and ribs too.", "why": "The grade encodes laceration depth and parenchymal/vascular involvement, which is exactly what dictates management: splenic grades I–III can be repaired or observed (especially in stable patients and children, to avoid OPSI), while IV–V — crush, bisection, hilar, or shattered — are not repairable and require splenectomy."}, "37_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Rose closes fast and by anecdote, so keep this tight. The pancreas is a crush injury: lying retroperitoneally across the spine, a focal midline blow can crush or even transect it against the vertebral column — his garbage-truck case bisected the pancreas right over the spine, repaired with a Roux-en-Y pancreaticojejunostomy. Work it up with amylase and lipase (also checked in lavage fluid), see it on CT/ultrasound, and use ERCP to define the ductal anatomy; expect severe back pain because there's no room in the retroperitoneum. Thoracoabdominal and pelvic trauma in a crashing multi-trauma patient is a team approach through a thoracoabdominal incision, working chest and abdomen at once.", "why": ""}, "38_1": {"answer": "ANATOMY FIRST. Moljo built the whole lecture around a single ED vignette — a 68-year-old woman with three days of left-lower-quadrant pain, low-grade fever and chills — and her one repeated instruction is to start with anatomy: \"for the abdominal exam… always start with anatomy.\" Name what lives in the painful quadrant (sigmoid colon, ovary, bladder) and the history questions write themselves. The classic tell is constant LLQ pain with fever; ask too about timing, change in bowel habits, urinary symptoms, and — in a woman — gynecologic causes, which is why she argued the declined pelvic exam still leaves a real gap (an ovarian source can masquerade as colonic pain). Notice the exam targets recognition here, not deep recall — you are pattern-matching a presentation, not memorizing a checklist.", "why": ""}, "38_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The workup runs on one idea Moljo built into a quiz slide: each test answers a specific question, and you order it to confirm a suspicion rather than to fish. The lab panel sorts the differential — CBC (infection? anemia from a GI bleed?), CMP (diabetes, electrolytes, and crucially renal function before contrast), CRP/ESR (inflammation), urinalysis and culture (UTI, the LLQ mimic), HCG (pregnancy in any woman of childbearing age), and blood cultures if she looks septic. Two of those — the CMP renal check and the HCG — exist specifically to make it safe to give contrast.", "why": "Choose a water-soluble contrast medium. If it leaks through a perforation it is harmlessly absorbed, whereas leaked barium causes barium peritonitis — a severe chemical peritonitis."}, "38_3": {"answer": "THE DEFINITIONS LADDER. The whole LO turns on keeping four terms straight, so climb the ladder deliberately. A diverticulum is a single sac-like outpouching of colonic mucosa through a weak point in the muscular wall; diverticula is just the plural. DiverticulOSIS is the presence of diverticula — often asymptomatic. DiverticulITIS is inflammation of a diverticulum, which is then subdivided into uncomplicated versus complicated (abscess, fistula, obstruction, or free perforation). Diverticular disease is the umbrella term for clinically significant, symptomatic disease — including diverticulitis, diverticular bleeding, and segmental colitis. The exam loves to swap osis and itis on you, so anchor it: -osis = the pouches, -itis = the pouches inflamed.", "why": "Diverticulum = a single colonic outpouching; diverticulosis = their presence (often asymptomatic); diverticulitis = inflammation of one (uncomplicated/complicated); diverticular disease = the symptomatic umbrella. A colonic diverticulum is a pseudodiverticulum because it herniates only mucosa/submucosa, not all wall layers."}, "38_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW — UNCOMPLICATED VS COMPLICATED. Every management decision forks on one split: uncomplicated diverticulitis (inflammation only) is managed medically, often outpatient; complicated disease (abscess, perforation, obstruction, fistula) needs a more aggressive, usually inpatient and sometimes surgical approach. The modern, high-yield shift lives on the uncomplicated side — and the entire complication ladder lives on the other.", "why": "Antibiotics are reserved for complicated disease or high-risk hosts (major comorbidity, immunocompromise, immunomodulating drugs, systemic disturbance). A fluoroquinolone (or TMP-SMX) does not cover anaerobes, so it must be paired with metronidazole; amoxicillin-clavulanate covers both alone."}, "39_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Alcohol is the disease Schneider opens with because it is everywhere — implicated in over 50% of liver-related deaths, contributing to 250,000 deaths a year and $3 billion in health-care cost. But the paradox he wants you to hold is that most people who abuse alcohol never get severe liver disease — only about 20% develop alcoholic hepatitis, cirrhosis, or both. So the lecture is really about who tips over, how you spot them on labs, and how the body handles ethanol in the first place.", "why": "Low platelets and an elevated PT/INR together call cirrhosis off the labs: portal hypertension enlarges the spleen, and the hypersplenic spleen sequesters platelets, while the failing liver underproduces the vitamin-K-dependent clotting factors II, VII, IX, and X, prolonging the PT/INR."}, "39_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Schneider opens his 'Hit Parade' of chronic liver diseases by telling you exactly how to study them — sort each one by who gets it, how it presents, the one diagnostic serology if any, and the treatment. Primary biliary cholangitis is the easiest to pin down: a cholestatic disease of middle-aged women with a single near-perfect antibody. (A naming note: he learned it as primary biliary cirrhosis for a career and now teaches it as primary biliary cholangitis — the deck still shows both, but 'cholangitis' is the current name because most patients never reach cirrhosis.)", "why": "The antibody is the antimitochondrial antibody (AMA), positive in 95% of PBC. The rheumatologist gets there first because PBC travels with other autoimmune diseases (Sjögren, CREST, RA): chasing one of those, they order a broad panel, AMA lights up, and the patient arrives already labeled."}, "39_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Schneider promised this one would be 'super fun' and that 'you'll get pimped on it by everybody' — translation: high-yield, learn it cold. Hereditary hemochromatosis is the disease of too much iron absorbed. It is autosomal recessive on chromosome 6, carries two classic mutations — C282Y and H63D — and is the most common single-gene inherited disorder in the white US population (about 1 in 10 are carriers, 1 in 200–300 homozygous). A 1980s genetic survey of an entire Kodak factory turned up iron overload everywhere among old-stock Caucasians — that is how common the gene is.", "why": "Excess iron is absorbed in the gut (2–4 vs 1 mg/day), accumulates over decades with no excretory escape, and deposits in every organ. Before cirrhosis, phlebotomy clears the load and prognosis is excellent; once cirrhosis develops it is irreversible and carries a 120× HCC risk — so catching HHC pre-cirrhosis changes the whole outcome."}, "39_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Wilson disease is the copper twin of hemochromatosis — and Schneider builds the whole LO on the contrast. It is autosomal recessive on chromosome 13, with over 100 mutations, which makes genetic testing less useful and the clinical presentation highly variable. Where HHC is a disease of the 4th–5th decade, Wilson is the young person's disease (median presentation 12–23, oldest diagnosed at 58). Michael J. Fox, diagnosed with young-onset Parkinson's, was famously worked up for Wilson's — the right reflex, even though he did not have it.", "why": "The copper defect is in excretion, not deficiency: absorption is normal but biliary excretion is decreased, so copper backs up into blood and urine. Ceruloplasmin ends up low because it is consumed by the disordered copper handling — a consequence, not the cause; a high level actually excludes Wilson."}, "39_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Schneider closes the Hit Parade with three diseases at breadth, not depth — learn each by its one signature. Autoimmune hepatitis (AIH) attacks hepatocytes; primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) attacks large bile ducts and lives next to IBD; alpha-1 antitrypsin (A1AT) hits liver AND lung. He warned that fourth-year students chronically blur the bile-duct diseases and forget the antibodies — so the antibodies and the PBC-vs-PSC split are the durable discriminators here.", "why": "Autoimmune hepatitis needs urgent steroids (it mimics viral hepatitis but can be fatal); PSC is diagnosed by ERCP with no serology ('chain of lakes' in a man with IBD); alpha-1 antitrypsin makes you think lungs — early emphysema in a non-smoker — as much as liver."}, "39_6": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Schneider calls this the most common cause of liver disease you will see in your career — and he means it: an estimated 100 million Americans (~25% of the population) have fatty liver, and in the U.S. it is arguably the #1-2 cause of cirrhosis, hepatocellular carcinoma, and liver transplant. The nomenclature changed to reflect the real driver: NAFLD is now MASLD (metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease) and NASH is now MASH. The whole topic is the metabolic twin of the alcohol story — two roads to a fatty liver.", "why": "The diagnosis is MASLD (metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease, formerly NAFLD) in a textbook metabolic-syndrome patient; the single discriminator is the transaminase ratio — her ALT > AST (78 vs 55) is the non-alcoholic pattern, whereas alcohol would have shown AST > ALT."}, "41_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Parmar runs this lecture as a two-part drug-class spine — laxatives first, antidiarrheals second — and the single most useful thing you can do is build the category map before you learn a single mechanism. He said it plainly and repeatedly: he is not expecting you to remember the doses; he wants you to know which class a drug belongs to, how it works, and its one signature adverse effect. Laxatives start with a definition — drugs that accelerate fecal passage or decrease fecal consistency, used primarily for constipation — and the recurring caution that they treat the symptom, not the underlying cause, so undiagnosed abdominal pain, IBD, or obstruction must be excluded first.", "why": "The spine is the two category maps: four laxative buckets (bulk-forming, softener/lubricant, osmotic, stimulant, plus the severe-constipation secretagogues) and four antidiarrheal buckets (opioid-antimotility, antisecretory, bile-salt resins, probiotics) — each agent slotted to its class with its mechanism and signature adverse effect."}, "41_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This is the deepest LO of the lecture — every drug slide leads with Mechanism of action, and Parmar spends most of his minutes here. The trick is to see that all the laxatives are variations on getting water into the stool and all the antidiarrheals on keeping it in the body; the testable detail is by what molecular route. Work down the laxative buckets first, then cross to the antidiarrheals.", "why": "Saline laxatives pull water in by poorly absorbed ions raising luminal osmotic pressure; lactulose by colonic bacteria fermenting it to organic acids (with ammonia trapping); linaclotide by agonizing guanylate cyclase-C to raise cGMP and secrete Cl-/HCO3-. The route is tested because it predicts the use and the adverse effects — lactulose's ammonia-trapping gives its hepatic-encephalopathy use, and GC-C secretion gives the diarrhea risk."}, "41_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Every drug slide carries therapeutic uses and adverse effects in parallel, and the exam pattern Parmar coaches is a drug-matching one: which agent for which condition, and which signature AE flags which agent. The organizing move is to learn one headline indication and one signature toxicity per drug, because that pairing is what a vignette keys off. Below, the high-emphasis ones.", "why": "Chronic stimulant-laxative (senna/anthraquinone) abuse is flagged by melanosis coli — benign brownish-black colonic-mucosa pigment from lipofuscin (plus cathartic colon, the lost-motility partner). The somatostatin analog octreotide is flagged by cholelithiasis, gallstones from the biliary stasis and fat malabsorption it causes."}, "41_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The contraindications here are flagged hard because they are the drug-matching traps a vignette is built to spring. The pattern to carry: for each agent, one setting where giving it is dangerous. A 'which drug do you withhold' question is far more likely than a dosing question. Below are the four that recur.", "why": "Antimotility agents are forbidden in infectious/inflammatory diarrhea (C. difficile, IBD, bloody/febrile stools) — risk of toxic megacolon and sepsis. Eluxadoline is forbidden in sphincter-of-Oddi dysfunction/pancreatitis/biliary obstruction (and >3 drinks/day). Bismuth is forbidden in children with viral illness (Reye, from the salicylate). Mineral oil is forbidden in aspiration-risk patients (aspiration pneumonia)."}, "41_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This LO is a discrete rationale trio, and the unifying idea is that these three agents control diarrhea by treating the underlying disease, not by braking the gut. Sulfasalazine and glucocorticoids quiet inflammatory bowel disease; octreotide shuts off tumor hormone secretion. Match each to the disease it actually treats and the question answers itself.", "why": "Sulfasalazine treats ulcerative colitis (its bacterially released 5-ASA is the anti-inflammatory); glucocorticoids treat moderate-to-severe IBD flares (UC and Crohn's) by reducing cytokine-driven inflammation; octreotide treats secretory diarrhea from neuroendocrine tumors (carcinoid, VIPoma) and refractory CID by inhibiting tumor hormone secretion. Each controls diarrhea by treating its disease driver."}, "42_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. This is the high-yield heart of the lecture, and Machini handed you the organizing trick on a single slide he put in red and double-starred — he told the class 'I want you to know this slide' and that your board exam pulled two questions from it. The trick is one sort: conjugation. The first three diseases — Crigler-Najjar I, Crigler-Najjar II, and Gilbert — are UNCONJUGATED (a problem making bilirubin water-soluble), and the last two — Dubin-Johnson and Rotor — are CONJUGATED (a problem getting already-conjugated bilirubin out of the cell). Get that boundary and the rest is detail. All five are autosomal recessive.", "why": "The first sort is conjugation: CN-I, CN-II, and Gilbert are unconjugated UGT1A1 (gene 2q37) defects; Dubin-Johnson and Rotor are conjugated. The two conjugated ones are separated by the black liver and the inverted 1:3 coproporphyrin ratio of Dubin-Johnson versus Rotor's absent pigment and ~5x total coproporphyrin."}, "42_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. The whole vascular block hangs on one anatomical fact Machini drilled — the liver has a dual blood supply, the portal vein plus the hepatic artery — so losing one channel is usually buffered by the other and the liver rarely truly infarcts. When flow does fail, it is the hepatocytes farthest from the oxygenated inflow — the centrilobular (zone 3) cells — that die first. Frame the disorders by where flow is compromised: impaired inflow (portal vein), intrahepatic (cirrhosis/sinusoidal), and outflow (hepatic vein, i.e. Budd-Chiari) — that Robbins grid predicts the whole presentation.", "why": "The dual supply (portal vein + hepatic artery) means loss of one channel is buffered, so true infarction is rare. When flow does fail, the centrilobular (zone 3) hepatocytes — farthest from the oxygenated periportal inflow — are most vulnerable and die first, which is why zone-3 necrosis is the hallmark of both shock liver and infarction."}, "42_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Machini compressed this into the last few minutes, but the anchor is simple: Budd-Chiari syndrome is hepatic-vein OUTFLOW obstruction — thrombosis of the major hepatic veins (AKA hepatic vein thrombosis, a congestive hepatopathy). Obstruct more than two hepatic veins and blood can't leave the liver, producing the triad of hepatomegaly, ascites, and liver dysfunction. It is the outflow end of the vascular spectrum — contrast it with portal vein thrombosis, the inflow end (LO 42.4).", "why": "Budd-Chiari obstructs the hepatic vein OUTFLOW (more than two major veins). That one fact predicts a dark, congested, enlarged liver with ascites grossly, and centrilobular (zone 3) congestion progressing to necrosis and fibrosis histologically — because blood backs up rather than failing to arrive."}, "42_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Portal vein thrombosis (PVT) is narrowing or blockage of the portal vein by clot — the INFLOW end of the vascular spectrum, the mirror image of Budd-Chiari's outflow block. Machini gave the class one anchor he called 'the only one point here you should know': there is NO necrosis — only inflammation, hepatocellular atrophy, and sinusoidal congestion. The reason is the recurring theme of this whole lecture — the liver's dual blood supply means the hepatic artery keeps the tissue perfused even when portal inflow is blocked, so cells atrophy but do not die.", "why": "The one point is that portal vein thrombosis produces NO necrosis — only inflammation, hepatocellular atrophy, and sinusoidal congestion. The liver's dual blood supply means the hepatic artery keeps the tissue perfused when portal inflow is blocked, so hepatocytes atrophy but do not die."}};
const SLIDES = {"31": {"dir": "31-32", "count": 33}, "33": {"dir": "33-34", "count": 106}, "35": {"dir": "35-36", "count": 69}, "37": {"dir": "37", "count": 43}, "38": {"dir": "38", "count": 20}, "39": {"dir": "39-40", "count": 72}, "41": {"dir": "41", "count": 41}, "42": {"dir": "42", "count": 24}};
